00:21:18.590 --> 00:21:22.540
But I must say that as somebody
who came here in summer,

00:21:22.540 --> 00:21:27.630
the end of August, from central
Europe, from the Czech Republic --

00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:31.570
as somebody who tries to make
clear to the Czech Republic

00:21:31.570 --> 00:21:33.750
that discussion about refugees,

00:21:33.750 --> 00:21:37.790
the history of refugee
policy is an important topic

00:21:37.790 --> 00:21:39.130
and shouldn't be ignored.

00:21:39.130 --> 00:21:44.330
Coming here right at the moment
when refugees were just streaming,

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:49.210
flowing across the region
was very difficult for me.

00:21:49.210 --> 00:21:53.470 position:56%
And it is a very strange feeling
watching the European refugee crisis

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:54.830
from abroad.

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:58.860
But it's also another
enriching perspective.

00:21:58.860 --> 00:22:04.530
One of my motivations
for researching refugees

00:22:04.530 --> 00:22:09.300
of Czechoslovakian refugee
policy was that if you look

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:12.710
at what has been written
about Jewish

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:17.640
and non-Jewish refugees during the
Nazi time, during the Holocaust,

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:20.830
there's been much focus
on western countries.

00:22:20.830 --> 00:22:24.550
Western Europe, United
States, United Kingdom.

00:22:24.550 --> 00:22:27.860 position:56%
And much less attention to the east.

00:22:27.860 --> 00:22:32.320
As if refugees were just a
topic of liberal democracies

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:34.510
and the question was
only, "How is it possible

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:40.150
that liberal democracies guided by
their values or not so have failed

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:41.450
to deal with the Holocaust?"

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:45.700
This is the very simplified notion
that you can see very often.

00:22:45.700 --> 00:22:52.330
However, refugees are also going
to the east, whatever it is.

00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:58.140
And it is also in eastern Europe or
if you want post-communist Europe

00:22:58.140 --> 00:23:01.830
where the history of refugees,

00:23:01.830 --> 00:23:07.580
the history of refugee
policy should be discussed

00:23:07.580 --> 00:23:12.340
and where society should try
to come to terms with that.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:14.590 position:56%
Would it help in the current crisis?

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:15.890
I don't know.

00:23:15.890 --> 00:23:20.440
But I believe it will
create a better environment,

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:26.340
more informed environment for
discussing where we are today.

00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:32.520
Czechoslovakia, and we are now
going to focus on Czechoslovakia,

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:35.320
is known historically, especially

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:38.170
in the integral period,
as a place of refuge.

00:23:38.170 --> 00:23:40.820
It is very often idealized.

00:23:40.820 --> 00:23:44.800
And the goal of our two
presentations is not necessarily

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:52.550 position:56%
to turn this upside down, but rather
to provide alternative perspectives

00:23:52.550 --> 00:23:56.240 position:56%
and more information for discussion.

00:23:56.240 --> 00:24:03.190
Let me start with a specific event.

00:24:03.190 --> 00:24:06.020
Shortly after midnight
on March 12th,

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:09.220
1938 an usually full train arrived

00:24:09.220 --> 00:24:12.220
at a Czechoslovakian border
station of Bratislava.

00:24:12.220 --> 00:24:18.640 position:56%
And those on board were not usual
passengers of a sleep night express.

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:22.460
Most of them had packed only
the most necessary items.

00:24:22.460 --> 00:24:24.660
After hearing the news
of the German troops

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:30.360 position:56%
and Gestapo approaching towards
Vienna via the Anschluss of Austria.

00:24:30.360 --> 00:24:35.180
For endangered anti-Nazi
activists and many Jews,

00:24:35.180 --> 00:24:39.380
the Czechoslovak border seemed
to be the best way and one

00:24:39.380 --> 00:24:43.490
of the last escape ways as
well to avoid the Nazi rule.

00:24:43.490 --> 00:24:48.540
Among them was Richard Berman,
journalist and a staunch critic

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:51.560
of the Austrian Christian
Social and [inaudible].

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:55.410
And he recorded his
excitement on arrival

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:57.820
into the free Czechoslovakia.

00:24:57.820 --> 00:25:01.260
I quote, "Finally I will
sail to Greece again.

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:03.950
I was delivered safe."

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:08.150
He therefore found it hard
to believe what followed

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:10.850
after the train pulled
into Bratislava.

00:25:10.850 --> 00:25:16.160
All refugees were forced out of the
train and after a couple of hours

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:19.990
of tense waiting they
were returned to what had

00:25:19.990 --> 00:25:22.960
in the meantime become
Nazi-ruled Austria.

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:29.480
In Burman's narrative, the image
of freedom, both personal and that

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:33.780 position:56%
of the country of Czechoslovakia,
this image turned in the description

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:38.690
of an ugly and prison-like waiting
room at the railway station.

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:42.140
And this is apparently a
description of a real place.

00:25:42.140 --> 00:25:46.500
This place can be viewed
as a symbolic expression

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:50.500
of the profound surprise
and disillusionment

00:25:50.500 --> 00:25:52.930
with democratic Czechoslovakia.

00:25:52.930 --> 00:25:56.160
Justs before being returned
to Austria, Burman managed

00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:59.280
to telegram the Czechoslovakian
president Edvard Benes,

00:25:59.280 --> 00:26:00.820
whom who he knew personally.

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:05.150
And you can see the
telegram on the slide.

00:26:05.150 --> 00:26:09.810
Appealing for the refugees
to be accepted.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:14.450
And this message ended up without
any reaction or any answer.

00:26:14.450 --> 00:26:16.300
It ended up in the archives

00:26:16.300 --> 00:26:20.010
of the Czechoslovakian
ministry of interior.

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:25.410 position:56%
I picked a little bit of the
language of that very short telegram

00:26:25.410 --> 00:26:28.890
and you can see that it
does appeal to the humanity

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:32.210
of the Czechoslovak democracy.

00:26:32.210 --> 00:26:35.840
And I'd like to connect this
with this element of surprise

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:39.220
that Burman must have experienced.

00:26:39.220 --> 00:26:41.480
And apparently he was
not the only observer

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:45.900
to perceive this contradiction
between the image

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:52.350 position:56%
of democratic Czechoslovakia and the
same country turning back refugees.

00:26:52.350 --> 00:26:57.410
He certainly could remember how
Czechoslovakia was deceiving

00:26:57.410 --> 00:26:58.710
anti-Nazi refugees.

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:05.860
In 1934 for instance, from
Austria, after the suppression

00:27:05.860 --> 00:27:10.910
of the leftist uprising in
Vienna and other cities,

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:14.530
when approximately
2,000 social democrats

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:20.030
and communists were
living in Czechoslovakia.

00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:25.980 position:56%
So the point I'm trying to make when
I focus on this particular event is

00:27:25.980 --> 00:27:33.440 position:56%
that what Burman couldn't understand
and what he was trying to come

00:27:33.440 --> 00:27:40.040
to terms with was one of the
most profound, important shifts,

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:42.010
if not the most important shift

00:27:42.010 --> 00:27:48.660
in the Czechoslovak refugee
policy in the 20th century.

00:27:48.660 --> 00:27:54.960
And apparently refugee policy
is all about categorization

00:27:54.960 --> 00:27:56.460
of people, unfortunately.

00:27:56.460 --> 00:27:58.150
Who is a refugee?

00:27:58.150 --> 00:27:59.910
What is this based on?

00:27:59.910 --> 00:28:02.890
What groups should be allowed on?

00:28:02.890 --> 00:28:05.470
And these refugees in Bratislava

00:28:05.470 --> 00:28:10.360
in 1938 witnessed a
shift of categories.

00:28:10.360 --> 00:28:14.580
First Burman and other perceived
themselves and others as opponents

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:19.040
of Nazism and the language
is connected to the language

00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:22.030
of political opposition to Nazism.

00:28:22.030 --> 00:28:24.930
So first they perceive
themselves as opponents of Nazism.

00:28:24.930 --> 00:28:27.780
Czechoslovak authorities
treated them as Jews,

00:28:27.780 --> 00:28:33.950
which meant in this particular
case, as unwanted Jewish migrants.

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:42.710
We do not have much time to discuss
Czechoslovak refugee policy before

00:28:42.710 --> 00:28:47.650
this point, but apparently interval
Czechoslovakia was not all bad.

00:28:47.650 --> 00:28:52.800
Interval Czechoslovakia
served as a refuge

00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:56.690
to refugees from the Soviet Union.

00:28:56.690 --> 00:29:04.110
It became a temporary home
to a lot of people escaping

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:09.320
from Nazi Germany, as well as to
the Austrians whom I mentioned.

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:14.550 position:56%
Most of these people who came before
1938 wouldn't experience something

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:15.850
like that.

00:29:15.850 --> 00:29:18.140
They wouldn't experience
refusal on the border.

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:22.250
They would have had a
program, especially the fact

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:26.420
that Czechoslovakia
wouldn't consider them

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:29.350
as permanent residents.

00:29:29.350 --> 00:29:36.290
Czechoslovakia is at this time
thought of rather as a place

00:29:36.290 --> 00:29:41.400
for temporary refuge before
the refugees will find a final

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:47.430
definitive home, for
instance somewhere overseas.

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:50.220
Yet if you look at a policy,

00:29:50.220 --> 00:29:54.890
a rather liberal policy
towards anti-Nazi refugees,

00:29:54.890 --> 00:30:00.190
starting with 1933, we can
see that all these groups

00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:03.190
that were excluded
from this tolerance.

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.510 position:56%
And in a very simplified way I could
say that these were two groups.

00:30:06.510 --> 00:30:11.890
One was people who were
considered to be eastern Jews,

00:30:11.890 --> 00:30:13.890
especially Jews of Polish origin.

00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:15.410
So stateless Jews.

00:30:15.410 --> 00:30:17.830 position:56%
And the other group were communists.

00:30:17.830 --> 00:30:21.530
I'm not going to go
into details about this,

00:30:21.530 --> 00:30:24.070
and we can leave it to discussion.

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:30.210
However, we can see in the second
half of the 1930's especially

00:30:30.210 --> 00:30:37.200
after the Nuremburg Laws, 1935 in
Germany, we can see that elements

00:30:37.200 --> 00:30:41.110
of ethnic categorization and
elements of, if you want,

00:30:41.110 --> 00:30:46.010
administered anti-Semitism,
are sneaking in in the practice

00:30:46.010 --> 00:30:47.850
of Czechoslovakia refugee policy.

00:30:47.850 --> 00:30:54.390
And it's a longer process
of categorizing all Jews,

00:30:54.390 --> 00:30:58.980
all Jewish refugees, as what
was called the eastern Jews,

00:30:58.980 --> 00:31:09.080
those who were unwanted, to those
who were understood to be something

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:15.030
in the very opposition to the
notion of proper citizenship.

00:31:15.030 --> 00:31:22.550
Thus the border closure of 1938
doesn't come out of nothing.

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:28.040
Now let me come back to 1938 and
just give you a couple of episodes,

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:31.440
and these are only examples.

00:31:31.440 --> 00:31:35.140
Throughout the spring
and summer of 1938,

00:31:35.140 --> 00:31:39.140
Czechoslovak border guards
were routinely hunting refugees

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:41.130
around the border with Austria.

00:31:41.130 --> 00:31:44.910
And along the swampy
banks of the Danube.

00:31:44.910 --> 00:31:49.940
And I don't know how many
refugees were turned back.

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:53.710
Neither do I know how many
made it into Czechoslovakia.

00:31:53.710 --> 00:31:56.690
But I've extrapolated
from very partial sources

00:31:56.690 --> 00:32:00.460
that there might be some 10,000
cases of return of refugees.

00:32:00.460 --> 00:32:04.100
Which is a large number for
those of us who can remember

00:32:04.100 --> 00:32:07.690
for instance the discussions
about the Swiss policy

00:32:07.690 --> 00:32:11.790
in 1938 and then again in 1942.

00:32:11.790 --> 00:32:15.180
These are very similar numbers.

00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:20.460
The Czechoslovakian and Swiss
numbers are rather similar.

00:32:20.460 --> 00:32:25.860
So there's never been a significant
discussion in the Czech Republic

00:32:25.860 --> 00:32:29.700
or Czechoslovakia about this event.

00:32:29.700 --> 00:32:32.180
On this particular slide,

00:32:32.180 --> 00:32:35.400
let me just make a short
remark about the map.

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:40.030
I picked up a map which
includes the events of 1939

00:32:40.030 --> 00:32:45.280 position:56%
so that you can see protectorate
Moravia, so occupied Czechoslovakia.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:49.840
In 1938, the time we talk
about, this is not yet the case.

00:32:49.840 --> 00:32:52.250 position:56%
But that was all the borders we need

00:32:52.250 --> 00:32:57.050
for understanding the
story that we discuss here.

00:32:57.050 --> 00:33:04.650
I've picked an event on
the shores of the Danube.

00:33:04.650 --> 00:33:10.390
A refugee from Vienna named Pavel
Kostner who was born actually

00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:13.480
in Czechoslovakia in
Bratislava, escaping from Vienna.

00:33:13.480 --> 00:33:18.430
He's caught by the Czechoslovakian
border police and they report

00:33:18.430 --> 00:33:24.120
in very cold language
how he committed suicide.

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:26.830
This is an extreme case.

00:33:26.830 --> 00:33:28.130
It's not typical.

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:29.430
It's an extreme case.

00:33:29.430 --> 00:33:35.900
But it testifies to the
very extremity of the nature

00:33:35.900 --> 00:33:39.050
of the Czechoslovakian
refugee policy.

00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:43.360
And Czechoslovakian refugee
policy was not exceptional.

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:47.570
It was typical at this time.

00:33:47.570 --> 00:33:53.860
The extremes of the refugee policy
were also illustrated on the fate

00:33:53.860 --> 00:33:55.370 position:56%
of a group of Jews from [inaudible].

00:33:55.370 --> 00:34:02.090
Jews who were brought by the
Austrian side during the night.

00:34:02.090 --> 00:34:06.450
One night in mid-April,
1938 across the Danube.

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:13.060
Czechoslovak officials found them
in the morning freezing, wet.

00:34:13.060 --> 00:34:14.360
They fed them.

00:34:14.360 --> 00:34:16.210
They sent them back immediately.

00:34:16.210 --> 00:34:20.420
And then the same thing was then
repeated on the Hungarian border.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:24.290
The group was subjected
to humiliating labor

00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:26.410
on the Austrian side of the border.

00:34:26.410 --> 00:34:32.070 position:56%
And had to survive in a region where
the borders of the three states met.

00:34:32.070 --> 00:34:36.480 position:56%
Eventually, the Bratislava community
found the only solution available

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:40.010
and accommodated them
on a towboat anchored

00:34:40.010 --> 00:34:42.190 position:56%
on the Hungarian side of the Danube.

00:34:42.190 --> 00:34:44.580
The Danube counted as
international borders.

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:49.170
That's why none of the three
states could really intervene.

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:53.770 position:56%
And here you can see a short excerpt
from a report about the situation

00:34:53.770 --> 00:34:56.380
on the boat and the
terrible situation.

00:34:56.380 --> 00:34:58.830
Suffering, spiritual and physical,

00:34:58.830 --> 00:35:02.290
to which these people
were subjected.

00:35:02.290 --> 00:35:05.200
It took three or four
months, during which none

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:10.000
of the three states was willing
to provide even a temporary refuge

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:14.590
to arrange for the emigration,
overseas, mostly to Palestine

00:35:14.590 --> 00:35:19.730 position:56%
and to the United States of America.

00:35:19.730 --> 00:35:28.070
Now the policy that was developed
towards Austrian Jews became model

00:35:28.070 --> 00:35:30.390
in 1938.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:36.000
And it was replicated against
other groups of refugees.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.980
But very interestingly, and
this is yet another shift

00:35:38.980 --> 00:35:42.170
in the Czechoslovakian
refugee policy.

00:35:42.170 --> 00:35:46.240
The groups that followed,
that were excluded,

00:35:46.240 --> 00:35:51.650
were Czechoslovak citizens,
former Czechoslovak citizens.

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:57.730
And their own country was trying
to not allow them or to expel them

00:35:57.730 --> 00:36:01.310
or to have them emigrate
as quickly as possible.

00:36:01.310 --> 00:36:04.390 position:56%
It was almost as an automatic reflex

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:07.240
that Czech officials
were sending back Jewish

00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:10.040
and also some German
refugees from Sudetenland

00:36:10.040 --> 00:36:12.080
after the Munich Agreement.

00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:14.000
And after the Christian Act.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:18.060
After the Munich Agreement,
the border areas

00:36:18.060 --> 00:36:23.980
of Czechoslovakia were
annexed to Nazi Germany.

00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:29.130
And they were also dumping
Jews with Polish citizenship

00:36:29.130 --> 00:36:32.860
across the border in Ostrava.

00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:38.530
And I've just included a quote
from a letter by Ilsa Verber,

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:41.690
in which she testifies
about the horrible scenes

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:43.790
in the no man's land.

00:36:43.790 --> 00:36:46.670
No man's land is a
proliferating term by this time.

00:36:46.670 --> 00:36:53.700
Into no man's land on the
Czechoslovak/Polish border.

00:36:53.700 --> 00:37:00.200
I could add many more events
on the Czechoslovak border

00:37:00.200 --> 00:37:02.790
of something I call not
just a physical border,

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:09.990 position:56%
but a border of citizenship in the
sense that refugees, and this is one

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:13.430
of my conclusions here
-- that the development

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:18.660
of the restrictive policy
towards refugees is essential

00:37:18.660 --> 00:37:25.790
in reframing the rules of
citizenship, also for those

00:37:25.790 --> 00:37:28.240
that are not yet refugees.

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:33.900
So that Jewish refugees coming from
the outside were contributing --

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:35.200
or rather the policy towards

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:39.420
such refugees was contributing
towards eroding the rights

00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:41.990
of Jews living inside
of the country.

00:37:41.990 --> 00:37:46.670
And one thing that is connected
with this is also a revision

00:37:46.670 --> 00:37:53.080
of citizenship in Czechoslovakia
instituted in January 1939,

00:37:53.080 --> 00:38:00.340
similar to for instance Polish or
Romanian revisions of citizenship.

00:38:00.340 --> 00:38:04.370
A revision of citizenship
which stripped Jews who escaped

00:38:04.370 --> 00:38:07.120
from Sudetenland of their
Czechoslovakian citizenship.

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:12.280 position:56%
I have just picked one single case
of a person, random case of a person

00:38:12.280 --> 00:38:16.940
who was denaturalized
in this process.

00:38:16.940 --> 00:38:27.280
Therefore, the refugees were
discounted citizenship became an

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:30.500
impulse, or perhaps
if you want a pretext,

00:38:30.500 --> 00:38:34.370
to revise citizenship
along ethnic lines.

00:38:34.370 --> 00:38:38.390
So refugees and citizenship are
always interconnected categories.

00:38:38.390 --> 00:38:44.190
And it's important that we
think about them in this way.

00:38:44.190 --> 00:38:47.040
As a conclusion,

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:52.750
1938 in Czechoslovakia is
certainly a turning point.

00:38:52.750 --> 00:38:55.860
And by this turning point,
Czechoslovakia ceased

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:59.530
to be a refuge, but
rather became a country

00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:02.470
that was generating refugees.

00:39:02.470 --> 00:39:05.230
It was a county which increasingly,

00:39:05.230 --> 00:39:10.430 position:56%
especially after the second World
War, understood itself as homogenous

00:39:10.430 --> 00:39:14.130
in terms of nationality
or ethnicity.

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:19.020
I just mentioned that
Czechoslovak Germans

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:25.530
and some Hungarians were expelled
after the second World War.

