Jews with Polish citizenship

01:11:42.120 --> 01:11:46.030
who are being basically channeled
through Czechoslovakia to Poland.

01:11:46.030 --> 01:11:48.940
And in Poland this leads to
a revision of citizenship.

01:11:48.940 --> 01:11:52.410
This revision of citizenship
will mean

01:11:52.410 --> 01:11:56.950
that Polish Jews living abroad
won't keep their Polish passports,

01:11:56.950 --> 01:12:00.280
or these Polish passports wouldn't
allow them to come back to Poland.

01:12:00.280 --> 01:12:05.090
This led to the expulsion of
Polish Jews from Germany at the end

01:12:05.090 --> 01:12:09.180
of October 1978, something
I haven't mentioned at all.

01:12:09.180 --> 01:12:12.190
And this is an event
which is also connected

01:12:12.190 --> 01:12:16.440
to this history of
the Kristallnacht.

01:12:16.440 --> 01:12:20.360
Perhaps a couple of words
about Czechoslovakia.

01:12:20.360 --> 01:12:24.430
As you have seen I have
largely skipped facts

01:12:24.430 --> 01:12:30.420
about the post-Munich refugees
simply because it's a huge topic.

01:12:30.420 --> 01:12:34.780
But we need to take into
account that this is one

01:12:34.780 --> 01:12:39.350 position:56%
of the most extensive bases of
refugees in Czechoslovakian history.

01:12:39.350 --> 01:12:43.010
Basically comparable only
to the first World War.

01:12:43.010 --> 01:12:49.340
It can be somewhere around say the
end of 1938 some 200,000 who escape

01:12:49.340 --> 01:12:51.540
after the Munich Agreement
or before,

01:12:51.540 --> 01:12:53.800
during and after the
Munich Agreement.

01:12:53.800 --> 01:12:57.260
And after the Kristallnacht
from the border areas.

01:12:57.260 --> 01:12:58.820
Most of them are Czechs.

01:12:58.820 --> 01:13:05.980 position:56%
But among them there are probably
some 20,000 Jews and 20,000 Germans.

01:13:05.980 --> 01:13:08.740
So I don't know if that answered.

01:13:08.740 --> 01:13:10.550
And these events are connected.

01:13:10.550 --> 01:13:13.260
There's a chain of events.

01:13:13.260 --> 01:13:17.290
&gt;&gt; The second question is a
personal question for all three.

01:13:17.290 --> 01:13:22.370
Do you all three have family
histories that went through this,

01:13:22.370 --> 01:13:26.410
that motivated you
to study this area?

01:13:26.410 --> 01:13:30.500
&gt;&gt; Gail Shirazi: Repeat
the question please.

01:13:30.500 --> 01:13:32.890
&gt;&gt; Michel Frankl: The
question is whether the three

01:13:32.890 --> 01:13:36.560
of us speakers have personal
histories, family histories

01:13:36.560 --> 01:13:42.200
that would motivate us
to deal with this topic.

01:13:42.200 --> 01:13:47.810
But in my case, my family histories
are connected to the Holocaust

01:13:47.810 --> 01:13:52.930
and partially also these
are refugee histories.

01:13:52.930 --> 01:13:56.100
But I'm not sure that
this motivated me

01:13:56.100 --> 01:13:59.920
to specifically look
into this topic.

01:13:59.920 --> 01:14:04.010
I started to deal with the
history of anti-Semitism

01:14:04.010 --> 01:14:06.780
when I was searching for
a topic for my BA thesis.

01:14:06.780 --> 01:14:09.710
And I discovered that the
topic, which I'm not going

01:14:09.710 --> 01:14:12.260
to describe here, is
largely undescribed

01:14:12.260 --> 01:14:15.740
and unanalyzed in the
historiography.

01:14:15.740 --> 01:14:18.860
&gt;&gt; Gail Shirazi: Katerina?

01:14:18.860 --> 01:14:20.870
&gt;&gt; Katerina Kralova: Well
you will be surprised.

01:14:20.870 --> 01:14:26.190
I have no other connection
than academic connection.

01:14:26.190 --> 01:14:29.570
And connection with my older years,

01:14:29.570 --> 01:14:32.610
which I spent in Greece
traveling for my research.

01:14:32.610 --> 01:14:36.800
I have no Greek family background.

01:14:36.800 --> 01:14:43.140
My research started
mainly with my Ph. D thesis

01:14:43.140 --> 01:14:47.180
on Greek-German relations
and a shade of Nazi past.

01:14:47.180 --> 01:14:51.130
And I was always asked if
I have a Greek background.

01:14:51.130 --> 01:14:56.240
And I was always pushed
that I should do something

01:14:56.240 --> 01:15:00.290
about Greeks living
in Czechoslovakia.

01:15:00.290 --> 01:15:05.580
And it was a big task and it was
a marvelous task and I did it.

01:15:05.580 --> 01:15:08.130 position:56%
But there is no personal connection.

01:15:08.130 --> 01:15:13.570
In fact, my grandmother
too, who is still among us,

01:15:13.570 --> 01:15:17.260
which I am very happy for,
she is a Holocaust survivor.

01:15:17.260 --> 01:15:22.200
So again, there are tragic
experiences in the family,

01:15:22.200 --> 01:15:25.650
but none of them is
related to Greece.

01:15:25.650 --> 01:15:29.770
But it's an amazing
topic to be researched.

01:15:31.380 --> 01:15:33.840
&gt;&gt; Amy Kaslow: Mine
will be very brief.

01:15:33.840 --> 01:15:35.590
The short answer is no.

01:15:35.590 --> 01:15:42.080
But a fierce determination to
learn and once you learn the plight

01:15:42.080 --> 01:15:46.640
of one people, it's irresistible
to learn that of others.

01:15:46.640 --> 01:15:49.370
&gt;&gt; Gail Shirazi: We have
time for one more question.

01:15:49.370 --> 01:15:53.260
&gt;&gt; My question is for
you, Dr. Kralova.

01:15:53.260 --> 01:15:58.210
I was happy to hear how
integrated the refugees were

01:15:58.210 --> 01:16:00.090
who came in the '40's.

01:16:00.090 --> 01:16:05.100 position:56%
And I know refugees that come to the
United States, they have the ability

01:16:05.100 --> 01:16:09.070
to become American citizens
without too much trouble.

01:16:09.070 --> 01:16:11.700
At the end you said
most of the dancers,

01:16:11.700 --> 01:16:13.830
the Greek dancers, are Czech.

01:16:13.830 --> 01:16:17.870
So why is it that after 70
years they're still identified

01:16:17.870 --> 01:16:20.370
as Czech if they never left?

01:16:20.370 --> 01:16:23.730
Are they Greek citizens?

01:16:23.730 --> 01:16:26.990
Or how does that work exactly?

01:16:26.990 --> 01:16:32.420
Or do they still live in Greek
enclaves in the Czech Republic?

01:16:32.420 --> 01:16:34.090
&gt;&gt; Katerina Kralova: Well
the question would be

01:16:34.090 --> 01:16:42.500
about citizenship reflecting
the Czech and Greek identities

01:16:42.500 --> 01:16:46.150
in Czech Republic nowadays.

01:16:46.150 --> 01:16:52.530
And how these people
achieve their acculturation

01:16:52.530 --> 01:16:55.230
and adaptation in a society.

01:16:55.230 --> 01:17:00.230
Of course I had 20 minutes and
I had to skip so many things.

01:17:00.230 --> 01:17:03.200
So of course it was
not always ideal.

01:17:03.200 --> 01:17:08.180 position:56%
And of course we have
mentionings, especially in archives.

01:17:08.180 --> 01:17:13.830
Never, ever did it come
up in oral testimony,

01:17:13.830 --> 01:17:15.650
which was very interesting.

01:17:15.650 --> 01:17:18.350
If we asked directly we
were a mixed up group.

01:17:18.350 --> 01:17:23.680
So it was not only Czechs who
were interviewing the Greek Civil

01:17:23.680 --> 01:17:25.090
War refugees.

01:17:25.090 --> 01:17:28.370
So we could say, you know,

01:17:28.370 --> 01:17:34.820
if you speak with a Greek Civil War
refugee maybe you will be more open

01:17:34.820 --> 01:17:40.500
about that experience you
experienced in the country.

01:17:40.500 --> 01:17:43.170
It never really came
up in the interviews

01:17:43.170 --> 01:17:46.820
which for me was very
interesting and I didn't expect it.

01:17:46.820 --> 01:17:50.300
However, in the archives,
and we have to admit

01:17:50.300 --> 01:17:56.360
that recording interviews
five years ago, six years ago,

01:17:56.360 --> 01:18:00.460
we couldn't reach to all the first
generation of people who were

01:18:00.460 --> 01:18:04.010
at adult age or elderly when
they came to Czechoslovakia.

01:18:04.010 --> 01:18:05.810
Maybe we would get another picture

01:18:05.810 --> 01:18:09.400
if we had done the
recording 20 years earlier.

01:18:09.400 --> 01:18:13.100
In archives we can trace.

01:18:13.100 --> 01:18:17.920
There was a certain xenophobia in
the beginning, but it was overcome.

01:18:17.920 --> 01:18:22.420
Now to the question of citizenship,
that's a very interesting question.

01:18:22.420 --> 01:18:24.150
Czechoslovakia in the time

01:18:24.150 --> 01:18:28.550
of the Cold War didn't
allow anybody in Greece.

01:18:28.550 --> 01:18:33.520
It was very complicated to the
law against those who were put

01:18:33.520 --> 01:18:39.890
in the group of communists,
and who therefore could lose

01:18:39.890 --> 01:18:44.030
or would lose their citizenship
once they leave the country

01:18:44.030 --> 01:18:46.030
because of political reasons.

01:18:46.030 --> 01:18:47.330
There were other groups.

01:18:47.330 --> 01:18:52.660
It was very interesting what
defines you as being Greek,

01:18:52.660 --> 01:18:56.130
which was the Greek
orthodoxy and the language.

01:18:56.130 --> 01:19:00.810
Greece until nowadays doesn't
acknowledge national minorities,

01:19:00.810 --> 01:19:04.070
only religious minorities,
the traditional one.

01:19:04.070 --> 01:19:06.490
So if you were Jewish,
if you were Muslim,

01:19:06.490 --> 01:19:08.360
then you were a religious minority

01:19:08.360 --> 01:19:11.480
but you won't be a Jew
as a national minority.

01:19:11.480 --> 01:19:19.530
You won't be a Turk as a
national minority and so on.

01:19:19.530 --> 01:19:23.760
So this is one of the
frames back to Greece.

01:19:23.760 --> 01:19:28.600
And in Czechoslovakia you were not
allowed to have double citizenship.

01:19:28.600 --> 01:19:33.060
So in this situation people
had to make the decision,

01:19:33.060 --> 01:19:40.850
"Do I take a Czech citizenship
and then will be more vulnerable

01:19:40.850 --> 01:19:42.730
to losing my Greek citizenship

01:19:42.730 --> 01:19:45.890
and maybe never have the
opportunity to go back?"

01:19:45.890 --> 01:19:49.460
Because Greeks see me
as a Czech citizen.

01:19:49.460 --> 01:19:53.720
Therefore I won't be able to
apply for my Greek properties

01:19:53.720 --> 01:19:55.950
and everything I lost
because of the war.

01:19:55.950 --> 01:20:00.560
So this was a very difficult thing.

01:20:00.560 --> 01:20:06.370
In fact, until the end of the
Cold War, only several thousand

01:20:06.370 --> 01:20:13.830
in all the years applied for
-- several hundred, sorry,

01:20:13.830 --> 01:20:16.450
applied for Czech citizenship.

01:20:16.450 --> 01:20:23.630
So virtually nobody of this group
of the primary 12,000-plus people.

01:20:23.630 --> 01:20:25.650
But the second generation more

01:20:25.650 --> 01:20:29.630
and more did not have
a Czech citizenship.

01:20:29.630 --> 01:20:33.220
It was complicated, especially once
they were able to cross the border

01:20:33.220 --> 01:20:36.810
and so forth because they didn't
have proper documentation.

01:20:36.810 --> 01:20:40.320
So travelling for the first time
back to Greece they had a kind

01:20:40.320 --> 01:20:44.020
of paper issued that they
can cross the borders,

01:20:44.020 --> 01:20:47.260
but nobody really knew what
does it mean, et cetera.

01:20:47.260 --> 01:20:50.580
So this was a complicated
situation of citizenship.

01:20:50.580 --> 01:20:56.650
On the other hand, we have to move
ourselves back to the Cold War.

01:20:56.650 --> 01:21:00.360
Crossing borders was not
an easy task back then.

01:21:00.360 --> 01:21:05.610
So you mainly and for most remained
in the country where you lived in.

01:21:05.610 --> 01:21:08.280
So you didn't really
have the feeling, "Oh,

01:21:08.280 --> 01:21:12.520
I can't go to neighboring Austria
because I don't have passport."

01:21:12.520 --> 01:21:13.820
You couldn't go anyway.

01:21:13.820 --> 01:21:18.970
So this is something we have to
understand and to base limits

01:21:18.970 --> 01:21:23.680
of globalized society where the
passport is a very important thing.

01:21:23.680 --> 01:21:27.170
Back then it was approached
in a different way.

01:21:27.170 --> 01:21:29.470
So this is an important thing.

01:21:29.470 --> 01:21:33.300
Speaking about Greek
dancers, it's interesting

01:21:33.300 --> 01:21:38.780
because the Greek dancers
are mostly being the first --

01:21:38.780 --> 01:21:40.890
not anymore -- they vary.

01:21:40.890 --> 01:21:44.300
Second and third generation,
many of them.

01:21:44.300 --> 01:21:49.810
But of course open
to the whole society.

01:21:49.810 --> 01:21:54.320
Locally there is a lot of
dancing being done on a more

01:21:54.320 --> 01:21:57.980
or less professional level.

01:21:57.980 --> 01:22:04.180
So they are still Greek dancers,
second and third generation,

01:22:04.180 --> 01:22:07.310
who are even doing all
their costumes by their hand

01:22:07.310 --> 01:22:09.570
as they did back in
the Cold War et cetera.

01:22:09.570 --> 01:22:13.740
And who are travelling
to Greek dance festivals.

01:22:13.740 --> 01:22:15.820
Then the group is mostly Greek.

01:22:15.820 --> 01:22:21.710
But doing it as a hobby in your
leisure time, the group changes.

01:22:21.710 --> 01:22:25.350
And of course because as I said,
remember in all the republic,

01:22:25.350 --> 01:22:27.350
and we have 13 communities now.

01:22:27.350 --> 01:22:31.800
So it's scattered in a little
country of 11 million people.

01:22:31.800 --> 01:22:36.920
You have 3,000 of Greeks who
are still that distinguished,

01:22:36.920 --> 01:22:39.330
which is very interesting.

01:22:39.330 --> 01:22:47.520
And they attach to those
activities the majority population.

